111. iura inventa metu. Laws, embodying distinctions of right and wrong, were invented: they were not made by nature ready to man's hand. Nature of herself drew no clear and evident line between right and wrong. They slide into each other by gradations‚ and there are gradations of crime, and ought to be gradations of punishment.
